<article class="comment" id="comment5746711" data-author="users/254679" data-subject="comments/5746711" data-dislikes="0" data-id="5746711">
<p class="avatar"><a rel="nofollow" title="NeoKoala" href="/users/NeoKoala"><img class="framed lazy" src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHZpZXdCb3g9IjAgMCA4MCA4MCI+PC9zdmc+" width="80" height="80" data-original="https://static.nintendolife.com/themes/nl.v10/images/avatar.jpg" alt="NeoKoala" /></a></p>
<div class="detail"><ul class="info"><li class=" first"><a class="num" rel="nofollow" href="news/2020/08/taiwanese_rating_suggests_that_the_original_no_more_heroes_is_heading_to_switch#comment5746711">46</a></li><li><a rel="nofollow" class="username accent" title="NeoKoala" href="/users/NeoKoala">NeoKoala</a></li><li class=" last"><time class="date age " datetime="2020-08-03T18:56:30+00:00"><span>Mon 3rd Aug 2020</span></time></li></ul>
<section class="text">
<p><a href="https://www.nintendolife.com/users/Severian" class="mention" data-username="Severian" rel="nofollow">@Severian</a> I believe it was also to avoid getting a CERO Z rating in Japan since that’s what happened to several of Suda games. They have a problem with human on human violence if there’s blood and gore (among other things). Not sure if it’s still happening there but mostly games that are labeled Z by Cero are legally regulated and cannot be sold or displayed on the main floor of stores (they could only be sold in stores that contain a “Z” room which is Adults only).</p></section>
